<Base title="Reflexive Verbs" breadcrumb={[{ label: "Grammar", href: "/reference/grammar" }, { label: "Pronouns", href: "/reference/grammar/pronouns" }, { label: "Reflexive Verbs" }]}>
  <article>
    <div class="hgroup">
      <h1>Reflexive Verbs</h1>
      <p class="hgroup-rule">Verbs where the action returns to the subject — always conjugated with a reflexive pronoun and être in compound tenses.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>What it is</h2>
      <p>
        A reflexive verb is a verb where the action returns to the subject. The subject performs an action on itself.
        Unlike English where "to wake up" doesn't use a reflexive pronoun, French uses <em>se réveiller</em> literally:
        "to wake oneself."
      </p>
      <p><em>Je me réveille.</em> — I wake myself up.</p>
      <p>
        This isn't just a pronoun pattern — it's a full verb category that conjugates differently from regular verbs.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The pronoun table</h2>
      <p>
        Reflexive pronouns match the subject. Unlike object pronouns, they don't have separate strong/weak forms:
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Subject</th>
            <th>Reflexive Pronoun</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>je</td><td>me (m')</td></tr>
          <tr><td>tu</td><td>te (t')</td></tr>
          <tr><td>il/elle/on</td><td>se (s')</td></tr>
          <tr><td>nous</td><td>nous</td></tr>
          <tr><td>vous</td><td>vous</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ils/elles</td><td>se (s')</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Conjugation in simple tenses</h2>
      <p>
        Reflexive verbs conjugate like regular verbs, but always include the reflexive pronoun before the verb.
      </p>

      <h3>Present</h3>
      <p><em>se réveiller (to wake up)</em></p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Form</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>je</td><td>me réveille</td></tr>
          <tr><td>tu</td><td>te réveilles</td></tr>
          <tr><td>il/elle/on</td><td>se réveille</td></tr>
          <tr><td>nous</td><td>nous réveillons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>vous</td><td>vous réveillez</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ils/elles</td><td>se réveillent</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Imparfait</h3>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Form</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>je</td><td>me réveillais</td></tr>
          <tr><td>tu</td><td>te réveillais</td></tr>
          <tr><td>il/elle/on</td><td>se réveillait</td></tr>
          <tr><td>nous</td><td>nous réveillions</td></tr>
          <tr><td>vous</td><td>vous réveilliez</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ils/elles</td><td>se réveillaient</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Futur simple</h3>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Form</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>je</td><td>me réveillerai</td></tr>
          <tr><td>tu</td><td>te réveilleras</td></tr>
          <tr><td>il/elle/on</td><td>se réveillera</td></tr>
          <tr><td>nous</td><td>nous réveillerons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>vous</td><td>vous réveillerez</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ils/elles</td><td>se réveilleront</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Conjugation in compound tenses</h2>
      <p>
        Reflexive verbs always use <strong>être</strong> as the auxiliary in compound tenses (passé composé,
        plus-que-parfait, etc.). This is the same auxiliary used by motion and state-of-being verbs (DR MRS VANDERTRAMP).
      </p>
      <p><em>Elle est partie.</em> — She left.</p>
      <p><em>Il s'est réveillé.</em> — He woke up.</p>

      <h3>Agreement rules</h3>
      <p>
        The past participle agrees with the direct object when the reflexive pronoun is the direct object.
        This is the key rule:
      </p>

      <p><strong>Direct reflexive</strong> — the action is done to oneself:</p>
      <p><em>Elle s'est lavée.</em> — She washed (herself). (se = direct object, feminine → agrees)</p>
      <p><em>Ils se sont regardés.</em> — They looked at each other. (se = direct object, masculine plural → agrees)</p>

      <p><strong>Indirect reflexive</strong> — the reflexive pronoun is indirect, the direct object is something else:</p>
      <p><em>Elle s'est lavé les cheveux.</em> — She washed her hair. (les cheveux = direct object, se = indirect → no agreement)</p>

      <p><strong>Reciprocal</strong> — each person does something to the other:</p>
      <p><em>Ils se sont regardés.</em> — They looked at each other. (each looked at the other)</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Common reflexive verbs</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>French</th>
            <th>English</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>se réveiller</td><td>to wake up</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se lever</td><td>to get up</td></tr>
          <tr><td>s'habiller</td><td>to get dressed</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se laver</td><td>to wash (oneself)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se brosser</td><td>to brush (oneself/hair)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se coiffer</td><td>to do one's hair</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se maquiller</td><td>to put on makeup</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se doucher</td><td>to shower</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se coucher</td><td>to go to bed</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se promener</td><td>to go for a walk</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se méfier</td><td>to be wary</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se souvenir</td><td>to remember</td></tr>
          <tr><td>s'ennuyer</td><td>to be bored</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se plaindre</td><td>to complain</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se battre</td><td>to fight</td></tr>
          <tr><td>s'inquiéter</td><td>to worry</td></tr>
          <tr><td>se trouver</td><td>to be (located)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

